body:
Disclaimer: I used AI to help write this report. It seems to be correct. Not sure I 100% agree with its solution of implementing std::error::Error would be sufficient to fix though, it should be possible to use a concrete Error type.


## Description:

In influxdb-rs v0.8.0, the try_into_query() method (generated by the #[derive(InfluxDbWriteable)] macro) returns Result<WriteQuery, Self::Error>. However, Self::Error is defined inside a private module generated by the derive macro, making it unusable in external code.
This makes it impossible to properly handle errors without using unwrap():

```
use chrono::{DateTime, Utc};
use influxdb::InfluxDbWriteable;
#[derive(InfluxDbWriteable)]
struct TestReading {
    value: f64,
    time: DateTime<Utc>,
}
fn main() {
    let reading = TestReading { value: 1.0, time: Utc::now() };
    let result: Result<influxdb::WriteQuery, _> = reading.try_into_query("test");

    match result {
        Ok(query) => println!("Query: {:?}", query),
        Err(e) => {
            // ERROR: cannot convert to Box<dyn std::error::Error>
            let boxed: Box<dyn std::error::Error> = Box::new(e);
        }
    }
}
```

## Compiler error:

```
error[E0277]: `influxdb::error::TimeTryFromError<...>` doesn't implement `std::fmt::Display`
  --> src/main.rs:22:53
   |
22 |             let boxed: Box<dyn std::error::Error> = Box::new(e);
   |                                                     ^^^^^^^^^^^ unsatisfied trait bound
```

## Root Cause

The derive macro in influxdb_derive-0.6.0/src/writeable.rs generates:
1. A private module named __influxdb_private:
      mod __influxdb_private {
       pub enum Error<T> { ... }
   }

2. An impl that sets Self::Error to the private type:
      impl InfluxDbWriteable for MyStruct {
       type Error = __influxdb_private::Error<DateTime<Utc>>;
       // ...
   }

## The problem is:

- __influxdb_private::Error<T> contains TimeTryFromError<TimestampTooLargeError, TryFromIntError> as a variant
- TimeTryFromError and TimestampTooLargeError (defined in influxdb/src/error.rs) only implement thiserror::Error, NOT std::error::Error
- Therefore __influxdb_private::Error<DateTime<Utc>> doesn't implement std::error::Error
- And cannot be converted to Box<dyn std::error::Error>

## Expected Behavior 

Users should be able to handle errors from try_into_query() using ? or map_err() in their own error handling patterns.

## Suggested Fix

Either:
1. Make the error type public - Re-export __influxdb_private::Error from the crate so users can name it, OR
2. Implement std::error::Error for the underlying error types - Add std::error::Error impl to TimestampTooLargeError and TimeTryFromError in influxdb/src/error.rs:
      // Current - only thiserror::Error
   #[derive(Clone, Copy, Debug, Error)]
   #[error("The timestamp is too large to fit into an i64.")]
   pub struct TimestampTooLargeError(pub(crate) ());

   // Needs: impl std::error::Error for TimestampTooLargeError

## Workaround

Users must currently use unwrap() or add #[allow(clippy::unwrap_used)].

## Environment:
- influxdb-rs: v0.8.0
- influxdb_derive: v0.6.0  
- Feature: chrono enabled
- Rust: 1.94

Right now, the conversion from influxdb::query::Timestamp::Microseconds to chrono::Datetime is incorrect:
```rust
            Timestamp::Microseconds(mis) => {
                let nanos = mis / 10000;
                Utc.timestamp_nanos(nanos.try_into().unwrap())
            }
```
In this case, `nanos` should be calculated by multiplying mis by MICROS_PER_NANO, which equals 1000. 

p.s. If I understand correctly, this bug affects the correctness of timestamps stored in the influxdb and, therefore, if one uses microseconds precision to store the data - the time of the data in the database would be incorrect.

According to [Use gzip compression](https://docs.influxdata.com/influxdb/v2.6/write-data/best-practices/optimize-writes/#use-gzip-compression), `influxdb` supports `gzip` compression. I think that `influxdb-rust` should support this.

<!-- Describe the feature you'd like. -->

```rust
//...
let enable_gzip = true;
let client = Client::new("http://localhost:8086", "test", enable_gzip);
//...
```

<!-- How could your feature be implemented? -->

I guess that we can use [flate2-rs](https://github.com/rust-lang/flate2-rs) to implement this feature.

If you agree with this feature, I'd like to implement this.
